result.execSummary:
The defendant Latia L. Fink was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony [Modifiers: Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Possession of Methamphetamine [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).
  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Conceal (<=$500) [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(d).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The Defendant is to complete AODA assessment and comply with any treatment recommended.  The Defendant is to undergo any counseling the agent finds appropriate and must comply with any recommended treatment/assessment/counseling.  Defendant may not withdraw from any ordered program without permission of the agent and/or provider. The Defendant to complete a phychological evaluation and follow through with any recommended treatment.  The Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety - no alcohol or drugs unless prescribed by a physician. Defendant to take all medications as prescribed.  For the first 6 months of probation, Defendant to obtain half time employment. After 6 months, the Defendant is to obtain and maintain full time employment and/or educational programming as recommended.   The Defendant is to have no contact with D.K., T.R., or known drug users.  The Defendant is to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  The Defendant is subject to random drug/UA/blood testing.  The Defendant is not to go into any bars, taverns or businesses where the primary purpose is to sell alcohol. Defendant to be screened for eligibility for Outagamie County Drug Treatment Court and participated if accepted. Defendant to not use or possess drugs or alcohol. Defendant to not live in a home where drugs or alcohol are present.  If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due, and/or other collection means, such as income assignment will be issued.

**12-09-2016 - Court amends judgment.  Court adds:  Defendant to enroll in and follow-up with a 45 day treatment (in-patient) at Maehnowesekiyah Treatment Center in Gresham, WI.
